{{coord|46|35|35.72|N|7|39|21.89|E|display=title}}
The '''Tropenhaus''' ({{lang-en|Tropic House}}) in [[Frutigen]], Switzerland, is a commercial project using [[geothermal energy]] from hot water flowing out of the [[Lötschberg Base Tunnel|Lötschberg base tunnel]] for the production of [[Introduced species|exotic]] fruit, [[sturgeon]] meat and [[caviar]] in a tropical [[greenhouse]] in the [[Swiss alps]].<ref name="Swissinfo">{{cite news|url=http://www.swissinfo.org/eng/front/Alpine_caviar_and_papayas_come_to_Switzerland.html?siteSect=107&sid=10149999|title=Alpine caviar and papayas come to Switzerland|last=Ochsenbein|first=Gaby|date=January 1, 2009|publisher=[[Swissinfo]]|accessdate=2009-01-03}}</ref> In 2007, the project received the ''Prix Evenir'', the Swiss petroleum industry's [[Swiss franc|CHF]] 50,000 award for sustainable development.<ref name="Tagi">{{cite news|url=http://sc.tagesanzeiger.ch/dyn/news/schweiz/747010.html|title=Preis fürs Tropenhaus Frutigen|date=2 May 2007|publisher=[[Tages-Anzeiger]]|language=German|accessdate=2009-01-03}}</ref>
The idea for the greenhouse was born in 2002 when it became apparent that the water continuously flowing out of the Lötschberg Base Tunnel<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/printedition/life/20070330/dd_trains30.art.htm|title=European rail lines taking a giant leap|last=Soriano|first=César G.|date=30 March 2007|publisher=[[USA Today]]|pages=6D|accessdate=2009-01-03}}</ref> could not be directly diverted to the local river, the [[Kander (Switzerland)|Kander]], as its temperature of {{convert|20|°C|°F}} would disrupt the biological rhythm of the endangered [[Salmo trutta fario|trout]] there.<ref name="Swissinfo" /> Rather than cooling the water artificially, wasting its thermal energy, tunnel engineers founded a start-up company to use the warm water to heat a greenhouse. Construction of the site, which started in May 2008 at a cost of CHF 28 million, was due to be completed at the end of 2009.<ref name="Swissinfo" /> [[File:Tropenhaus Frutigen Plan.svg|left|230px|thumb|Layout]] A [[fish farm|sturgeon farm]], one of few in Europe, is the heart of the ''Tropenhaus''. Some 60,000 fish are intended to be grown in 40 outdoor basins.<ref name="Bund">{{cite news|url=http://www.tropenhaus-frutigen.ch/downloads/presse_ueber/bund17-05-08.pdf|title=Papayas und Kaviar aus Frutigen|last=Regli|first=Susanna|date=17 May 2008|publisher=[[Der Bund]]|language=German|accessdate=2009-01-03}}</ref> The sturgeons thrive in permanent Siberian summer conditions and are intended to yield 20 tonnes of meat as well as two tonnes of caviar annually.<ref name="Swissinfo" /> The first sturgeon fillets were sold in local stores in November 2008.<ref name="Oberländer 2008-11-08">{{cite news|url=http://www.tropenhaus-frutigen.ch/downloads/presse_ueber/bo_8_11_08_innen.pdf|title=Bald reifen tropische Früchte|last=Kühner|first=Andreas|date=8 November 2008|publisher=[[Berner Oberländer]]|language=German|accessdate=2009-01-03}}</ref> The rest of the greenhouses are dedicated to the production of exotic fruit, such as [[banana]], [[papaya]], [[mango]] and [[guava]], of which about 10 tons are intended to be grown annually in an area of {{convert|2000|m2|sqft|sigfig=3|abbr=on}}.<ref name="Swissinfo" />
The ''Tropenhaus'' is also intended to be a tourist destination, with a visitors' centre, a visitors' trail through the installation, a restaurant, and an exhibition room (paid for by a Bernese energy company) showcasing the project's use of renewable energy and sustainability. It is located some {{convert|600|m}} or 7 minutes' walk from [[Frutigen railway station]].<ref name="Swissinfo" /><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.tropenhaus-frutigen.ch/en/information/how-to-find-us | title = How to find us | publisher = Tropenhaus Frutigen | accessdate = 2013-10-24}}</ref> {{-}}
