{{Infobox scientist | name = Vicky Forster | workplaces = [[The Hospital for Sick Children]] | alma_mater = [[Newcastle University]] [[Durham University]] | thesis_title = AML1/ETO promotes a mutator phenotype in t(8;21) acute myeloid leukaemia | thesis_url = http://ethos.bl.uk/OrderDetails.do?uin=uk.bl.ethos.606731 | thesis_year = 2012 | known_for = Paediatric cancer }}
'''Victoria Jane (Vicky) Forster''' is a postdoctoral researcher at [[The Hospital for Sick Children]].
== Education == Forster grew up in Chelmsford, Essex. She was diagnosed with [[acute lymphoblastic leukemia]] aged 7.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2012/jul/01/vicky-forster-cancer-science-newcastle|title=Woman fights cancer as a patient - and then as a scientist|last=Thunder|first=Jamie|date=2012-06-30|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-03-26}}</ref> She became interested in scientific research whilst at hospital, and went on to study [[Biomedical sciences|biomedical science]] at the [[Durham University]].<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://scienceblog.cancerresearchuk.org/2012/12/12/dear-cancer-i-beat-you-aged-eight-and-today-i-got-my-phd-in-cancer-research/|title="Dear Cancer, I beat you aged eight and today I got my PhD in cancer research"|work=Cancer Research UK - Science blog|access-date=2018-03-26}}</ref> She graduated from [[Durham University]] in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theconversation.com/profiles/victoria-forster-128558|title=Victoria Forster|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2018-03-26}}</ref> Forster completed a PhD at [[Newcastle University]] with James Allan and Olaf Heidenreich.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jane|first=Forster, Victoria|date=2012|title=AML1/ETO promotes a mutator phenotype in t(8;21) acute myeloid leukaemia|url=http://ethos.bl.uk/OrderDetails.do?uin=uk.bl.ethos.606731}}</ref> On the day she finished her PhD, she tweeted ''‘Dear Cancer, I beat you aged eight and now I’ve got a PhD in cancer research’,'', and it went viral.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://futurefund.co.uk/dear-cancer-dr-vicky-forsters-story/|title=Dear Cancer - Dr Vicky Forster's story|website=futurefund.co.uk|language=en-US|access-date=2018-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-18723723|title=Ex-patient heads cancer cure bid|date=2012-07-06|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-03-26|language=en-GB}}</ref>
== Career == Forster used the media attention to praise where she worked, the [[Northern Institute for Cancer Research]], Newcastle upon Tyne.<ref name=":1" /> Here she concentrated on [[leukemia]] caused by mutations in DNA.<ref name=":1" /> Today Forster is a [[postdoctoral researcher]] at [[The Hospital for Sick Children]].<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sickkids.ca/Research/AbouttheInstitute/Profiles/GGB/forster-profile.html|title=Profile of Victoria Forster|last=Children|first=The Hospital for Sick|website=www.sickkids.ca|language=en|access-date=2018-03-26}}</ref> Her research focusses on the rare genetic disorder biallelic mismatch repair deficiency.<ref name=":2" />
In 2014 Forster was a British Science Association Media Fellow.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ourfutures.co/project/victoria-forster|title=Victoria Froster – Our_Futures|website=ourfutures.co|access-date=2018-03-26}}</ref> That year, she spoke at [[TED (conference)|TED]] x [[Jesmond Dene]] about the legacy of [[Janet Rowley]].<ref>{{Citation|last=TEDx Talks|title=Dissecting DNA to cure cancers - the legacy of Dr. Janet Rowley {{!}} Victoria Forster {{!}} TEDxJesmondDene|date=2014-07-23|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Qqmd9CRaDFM&feature=youtu.be|accessdate=2018-03-27}}</ref> She appeared in the science communication project [[Soapbox Science]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Soapbox Science|title=Dr Vicky Forster on being a Soapbox Scientist|date=2015-06-29|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xfAMcRYFKhs&feature=youtu.be|accessdate=2018-03-27}}</ref> Forster was a 2017 [[TED Fellow|TED Global Fellow]] researching [[Pediatric cancers|paediatric cancer]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://fellowsblog.ted.com/get-to-know-the-extraordinary-new-class-of-ted-fellows-5bd01d2c5dfc|title=Get to know the extraordinary new class of TED Fellows|date=2017-08-21|work=TED Fellows|access-date=2018-03-26}}</ref> Her [[TED (conference)|TED]] talk, ''What can cancer survivors teach us about cancer treatment'', was in [[Arusha]], Tanzania.<ref>{{Citation|last=TED Archive|title=What can cancer survivors teach us about cancer treatment? {{!}} Victoria Forster|date=2018-02-27|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XJVKF6tTHvI&feature=youtu.be|accessdate=2018-03-26}}</ref> She was listed in the 2017 [[Forbes 30 Under 30]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/victoria-forster/|title=Victoria Forster|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-03-26|language=en}}</ref> She has written for The Times, The Conversation, Forbes Health and The Guardian.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/victoriaforster/#6bf52bf76cc9|title=Victoria Forster|last=Forster|first=Victoria|website=Forbes|access-date=2018-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/childhood-cancer-survivors-face-risk-of-early-death-lcr2r7d72hh|title=Childhood cancer survivors face risk of early death|last=Forster|first=Vicky|date=2014-08-30|work=The Times|access-date=2018-03-26|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theconversation.com/profiles/victoria-forster-128558/articles|title=Victoria Forster|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2018-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/occams-corner/2016/jul/04/why-brexit-is-bad-news-for-cancer-research|title=Why Brexit is bad news for cancer research|last=Forster|first=Victoria|date=2016-07-04|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-03-26}}</ref> She is a member of the Society of [[International Society of Paediatric Oncology|The International Society of Paediatric Oncology]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://siop-online.org/blog/whos-behind-the-blog/|title=Who is behind the Blog?|last=|first=|date=|website=The International Society of Paediatric Oncology|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-03-26}}</ref>
